label("$B$",(0,20),W);
label("$C$",(20,20),E);
label("$D$",(20,0),E);
label("$E$",(0,0),W);
[/asy] ||| To find angle CAD, we note that triangle ABC is equilateral, so \angle ABC = 60^\circ. The angles around point C total 360 degrees, and we also have a right angle at D, thus \angle BCD = 90^\circ. So, we have \angle ACD = \angle ABC + \angle BCD = 60^\circ + 90^\circ = 150^\circ. Now, applying the triangle sum theorem in triangle ACD: 
 \begin{align*}  m\angle CAD + m\angle CDA + m\angle ACD &= 180^\circ \\  m\angle CAD + m\angle CAD + 150^\circ &= 180^\circ \\  2m\angle CAD &= 30^\circ \\  m\angle CAD &= \boxed{30} \text{ degrees}. \end{align*}

